   id="s4-2"
  
  
>

    <header class="article-section__header">
      <h3 class="article-section__header_text">Network architecture and neuron model</h3>
      
        <a href="https://bio-protocol.org/eLIFErap34560?item=s4-2" class="article-section__header_link">Request a detailed protocol</a>
    </header>

  <div class="article-section__body">
      <p class="paragraph">We study a feedforward network where a single output neuron receives synaptic input from <math id="inf30"><msub><mi>N</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">E</mi></msub></math> excitatory and <math id="inf31"><msub><mi>N</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">I</mi></msub></math> inhibitory neurons (<a href="#fig1">Figure 1a</a>) with synaptic weight vectors <math id="inf32"><mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0"><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="bold">w</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">E</mi></mrow></mrow></msup><mtext></mtext><mo></mo><mtext></mtext><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><msub><mi>N</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">E</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></msup></mrow></mstyle></math>, <math id="inf33"><mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0"><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="bold">w</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">I</mi></mrow></mrow></msup><mtext></mtext><mo></mo><mtext></mtext><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><msub><mi>N</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">I</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></msup></mrow></mstyle></math> and spatially tuned input rates <math id="inf34"><mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0"><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="bold">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">E</mi></mrow></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="bold">x</mi><mo mathvariant="bold" stretchy="false">)</mo><mo></mo><msup><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold">N</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">E</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></msup></mrow></mstyle></math>, <math id="inf35"><mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0"><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="bold">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">I</mi></mrow></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="bold">x</mi><mo mathvariant="bold" stretchy="false">)</mo><mo></mo><msup><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold">N</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">I</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></msup></mrow></mstyle></math>, respectively. Here <math id="inf36"><mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0"><mrow><mi mathvariant="bold">x</mi><mo></mo><msup><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">d</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">i</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">m</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">e</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">n</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">s</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">i</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">o</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">n</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">s</mi></mrow></mrow></msup></mrow></mstyle></math> denotes the location and later also the head direction of the animal. For simplicity and to allow a mathematical analysis we use a rate-based description for all neurons. The firing rate of the output neuron is given by the rectified sum of weighted excitatory and inhibitory inputs:</p>
<div class="math-block" id="equ1">

    <span class="math-block__label">(1)</span>

